{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_ferengi_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383345959/1930100301/0329.xml":{"full_text":"Assuring Signs Come to Fore in Confused But Bettering Business;\nTRADE IS IMPROVING\nIN VARIOUS AREAS,\nDUN\u2019S REVIEW FINDS\nProgress Out of Summer Dull-\nness Is Irregular but, on\nWhole, Encouraging\nLOW PRICES ATTRACTING\nCertain Raw Materials Such\nBargains as to Inspire Or\nders; Steel Betters\nEven in a situation which still has\nmany confusing and uncertain ele\nments, with accented unsettlement in\nspeculative markets, the more prom\nising signs in business are not ob\nscured, says R. G. Dun Co.\u2019s weekly\nreview of trade. It continues:\nSurvey\u2019s of individual lines con\ntinue to disclose numerous irregular\nand unsatisfactory phases, but condi\ntions viewed in their entirety reveal a\nmoderately better trend. Reports from\nt\u2019 different sections of the country,\ncovering widely diversified trades, re\nflect a maintenance jof the gradual\ngains that began with the passing of\nt' e summer, with a slow broadening\nof the circle of improvement. Nothing\nin the current dispatches warrants\nother than conservative expectations,\nyet the composite sentiment is more\ncheerful. Since confidence is essential\n*to commrcial progress, particularly\nafter a period of stress, the present\ndisposition to regard the outlook more\nhopefully is encouraging. Consider\nar 2 already has been accomplished in\nlaying a foundation for ultimate gen\neral economic recovery, and the ad\n-stments which yet remain to be\ncompleted appear to be, as a whole,\nlc:s disturbing.\nThat certain raw materials and\nsemi-finished products are believed\nto be an advantageous purchase at\nexisting low prices is indicated by the\nwillingness of some buyers to con\ntract ahead, but various other com\nmodities are in a more unstable po\nsition and forward commitments are\ndiscouraged. Even eliminating food\nstuff's, Dun\u2019s list of wholesole quota\ntions lacks evidence that a definite\nturning point has been reached, al\nthough declines recently were not so\npreponderantly in the majority.\nIt was not to be anticipated, follow\ning a protracted transition, that a\nsingle month would bring a decisive\nbusiness revival, and the factor of\nseasonal stimulus is not to be dis\nregarded in September\u2019s betterment.\nAny change in the right direction,\nhowever, is something gained, and\nsome additions to factory forces, al\nthough scattered, are a favorable\nr-gury.\nThus far, only a few of the statts\n1' al barometers have reflected a re\nversal of the prolonged recession, yet\nsteel output has risen a little more,\nwithout the support of important or\nders from some of the larger con\nsumers, and railroad freight traffic is\nshowing the tendency toward upturn\nwhich normally comes during the\na\" mn.\nSpeculative Markets Still Unsettled\nThe unsettlement in speculative\nmarkets has resulted in still lower\nprices for stocks, grains a:.! cotton.\nMuch of the upset, especially in grains\nand stocks, was due to rumors of an\nunfavorable character, and the price\ndeclines were accelerated by rather\naggressive bearish operations. New low\nlevels for both wheat and cotton were\nrecorded, while stocks dropped abrupt\nly at time-; and certain Issues broke\nthrough their previous bottom points.\nRallies were, for the most part, in\ndecisive, the prevailing trend being\ndownward.\nA feature apart from the specu\nlative disturbance was the further eas\ning in money rates, with funds for the\nfixed periods receding to the lowest\nbasis in many years. Thus, loans for\nfovtr to six months were quoted at\nto 2% per cent, which contrasted in\na striking way with the charges of\n9 ~nd 914 per cent named a year ago.\nSteel, Textiles, Hides\nNews from the steel industry this\nweek, as was to be expected, lacks\nuniformity, but further indications of\nbetterment appeared.\nWhen allowance is made for the\nobservance of the Jewish holidays this\nweek, the more favorable character\nistics recently developed in the textile\ntrades have been maintained. Moderate\njgains have been the rule, but the\nmore encouraging trend has been dis\ntinct, and some prices are steadying.\nRecurring periods of unsettlement\nin hide markets continue, the latest\ntrend being in a downward direction.\nEdgar Claton Mount\nWas Baldwin Pioneer\nAnd Native of lowa\nEdgar Claton Mount, who died at\nthe family homestead near Baldwin\nat 12:30 o\u2019clock, Wednesday noon,\nSeptember 24, 1930, of heart trouble,\nafter an illness of two years, was the\noldest son of Mr. and Mrs. Matt\nMount, of Herndon, la. He was born\nOct. 25,1870, in Guthrie county, lowa,\nand was 59 years. 10 months. 29 days\nof age at death. He had been con\nfined to his bed most of the time\nsince March 1.\nMr. Mount was united in marriage\nto Alice Eldora Mount, April 30. 1894,\nat Guthrie Center. la. Mrs. Mount\npreceded him in death two and one\nhalf years ago.\nMr. Mount and his family came\nfrom Panora. lowa, in the year 1902,\ntaking up a homestead in the Bald\nwin ccmmunity, where he then made\nhis home for the past 28 years. In\nthis time he became one of the lead\ning residents of his township He\nserved on the school board 18 years\nand was county assessor for a num\nber of terms.\nFive children blessed this union,\nall of whom are living. They are:\nNeva, Lela and Harold at home;\nJohn, of Driscoll; Qecil. of Wilton.\nThere are two grandchildren at Wil\nton. The following sisters and\nbrothers are living: Mrs. Fred Rente\nley. Bagley Mrs. Jim MolUe. Cooper.\nMrs. E. C. Gardner. Clear Lake. Mrs.\nGeorge Jones. Guthrie Center. Virgle\nMount, Grand Junction. Lige Mount,\nOUT OUK WAY\nBRIDGE\nArticle No. 15\nBy WM. E. M\u2019KENNEY\nSecretary American Bridge League\nAt auction or contrr it is very\nnecessary that the bridge player have\na full knowledge of leads, proper re\nsponses and the messages they convey\nto partner. The most important of all\nleads is the original or opening lead.\nWhen partner has bid, the leads are\ndivided into two classes\u2014leads against\na no trump declaration, .and leads\nagainst a suit declaration.\nToday we will consider leads against\na no trump declaration.\nWhen partner has bid and your\nhand contains any strength in part\nner\u2019s suit, it is generally good bridge\nTOMORROW\n\u2018Problems which arise in leading\nagainst a suit declaration, when\npartner had bid, will be discussed\nby Mr. McKenney in his bridge\narticle in tomorrow\u2019s Tribune.\nto open this suit. The exception, of\ncourse, is when you have a strong\nsuit of your own with reentries. Re\nmember that you are endeavoring to\nattack the enemy and it is useless to\noperi a suit of your own without re\nentries, because you may establish It\nand never get in to cash in the estab\nlished cards.\nThe opening leader should bear in\nmind that, when partner has bid, that\nsuit usually contains length and\nstrength, and partner\u2019s hand also con\ntains a reentry. The correct card to\nlead when partner has bid is the\nhighest, except when holding four of\npartner\u2019s suit to the ace, king or\nqueen, when the fourth best should\nbe led. Some players, when holding\nace x x, king x x, or queen x x, will\nlead the lowest card, but this does not\ngenerally prove profitable. By leading\nthe highest card, partner can imme-\nCooper, all of Iowa; and James\nMount and Mrs. Ida Thompson, of\nCalifornia.\nFuneral services were held at the\nfamily home Saturday, September 27,\n1930, at 2:30 o\u2019clock, Rev. G. W.\nStewart, of Mandan, N. D., conduct\ning them. Mrs. Frank Barnes, of\nBismarck, sang \u201cBeautiful Isle of\nSomewhere,\u201d and \u201cJesus, Lover of My\nSoul.\u201d A large number of friends\nand nelghobrs came from far and\nnear to pay their last respects.\nPallbearers were Henry McCul\nlough, Herbert Little, Joe Varley, Wil\nliam Fricke, Burl Monroe and Her\nman Kickul, Sr.\nMr. Mount had \u2019*een a member of\nthe Modern Woodman lodge since he\nwas 21 years of age, joining at Hern\ndon, lowa.\nArvold Brings Back\nEuropean Stage Ideas\nFargo, N. D., Oct. 3.\u2014His travel\nbook filled with what the old world\nhas to offer in the realm of play and\nrecreation, Alfred G. Arvold Is back\nin his Little Country theater.\nThe North Dakota Agricultural\ncollege drama director and instructor\nhas just completed a 14-weeks tour\nthroughout Europe, representing the\nAmerican Country Life association as\nan official collaborator of the U. S.\nDepartment of Agriculture.\nAt the International Country Life\nconference at Liege, Belgium, Mr.\nArvold spoke on \u201cSocial Factors In\nAmerican Country Life.\u201d Other\nplaces of interest visited were Shake\nspeare\u2019s birthplace, the Vienna fair,\nand 4he Passion Way at Oberammer\ngau.\nIn Oslo, Arvold visited the birth\nplace and haunts of Henrik Ibsen,\nNorwegian author, whose plays Pro\nfessor Arvold has produced with con\nsiderable success.\nThe world's largest canal /lock, a\nquarter of a mile long and capable\nof raising the biggest ships. was re\ncently opened In Holland.\ndiately read what high cards of that\nsuit are held in the declarer's hand.\nWhen you open your partner\u2019s suit\nfourth best and later follow with an\nother card of that suit, your partner\nimmediately knows that you hold four\nof his suit with one of the three top\nhonors.\nTheie are times, of course, when\npartner\u2019s suit is not opened, and they\ncome under the following classifica\ntions:\nI.\u2014Supposing partner bids one suit,\nyou bid another suit, and your partner\nsupports that suit. If you are especial\nly ,v:::.k in your partner's suit It will\npay to open your own. Of course this\ncondition is not often found, as it is\nvery difficult for opponents to go into\nno trump if you and your partner\nl~~ve named two suits.\n2. -If your own suit is headed by\nace, king and queen your proper open\ning would be the king of your suit.\n3. If you have sure reentries in\nyour hand and have a strong suit\nheaded by king, queen, and you are\nweak in your partner\u2019s suit, it would\npay to open your own suit.\n4. If you hold a singleton of part\nner\u2019s suit, a long suit of your own\nwith sure reentries, it may pay to\nopen your own suit.\n5. Holding ace, king, jack, or a\nfive-card suit headed with the king,\nqueen, jack, the leader should open\nthe king, and then switch to partner\u2019s\nI suit.\nLater on a table of leads will be\ngiven that will show the player what\ncard to open holding various com\nbinations.\nThe opening leader should remem\nb: that it requires only nine tricks\nfor the declarer to go game at no\nLump, and unless he starts to attack\nthe declarer at what seems to be his\nweakest point immediately, the de\nclarer may establish his long suit and\nthereby go game.\n(Copyright, 1930, NEA Service, Inc.)\nAkron-Wyoming Stock\nWill Be Sold at Not\nLess Than Par Value\nNo more stock in the Akron-\nWyoming oil company will be issued\nfor less than par value, it was de\ncided at a meeting of representative\nstockholders and directors in the\nPatterson hotel here, according to\nDr. C. C. Hibbs, one of the stock\nholders.\nThe group) according to Dr. Hibbs,\ncame to this decision after deciding\nthat the holdings of the company in\nthe Oregon Basin Oil field were of\ngreat importance and in view of the\nfact that federal court at Cheyenne,\nWyo., had cleared title to the prop\nerty in favor of the Akron-Wyoming\ncompany.\nThe majority of the stockholders\nin the company are in Washburn,\nWilton, Bih.iarck, and other North\nDakota points, according to Dr.\nHibbs.\nStraw Sugar Occupies\nUniversity Chemists\nGrand Forks, N. D., Oct. 3.\u2014Over\nthe vast Nc Dakota prairies, dotted\nh. e and there, are numerous straw\nstacks. It would be a stretch of the\nimagination to see them turned into\nsugar. Yet it may be done in the\nf-Lure.\nThe chemistry research department\nat the University of North Dakota Is\nexperimenting to liifd the food value\nin the carbohydrate, xylose. This sugar\nIs obtained by the hydrolysis of carbo\nhydrates which are present In wood,\ne' 7, bran, and like materials.\nXylose has also been found In peanut\nshells and cotton seeds.\nIf xylose can be utilized by the\nl 88 a :ar it will make a cheap\ns-.bstitute for cane an<j best suggr\nWork on this experiment w** started\nduring the past summer term at the\nuniversity.\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE. FRIDAY, OCTOBER 3, 1930\nWallace and Norling\nTo Demonstrate Steer\nGrades for Farmers\nWashburn, N. D., Oct. 3.\u2014Farm\ners interested in a better under\nstanding of grades of feeder and\nprime steers will have an opportun\nity to see these grades demonstrated\nby J. K. Wallace, of the U. S. De\npartment of Agriculture, and A. L.\nNor ling, McLean county agricultural l\nagent, in cooperation with the county\nFanners' Union.\nDemonstrations will be conducted\nSaturday, October 4, dt the Frank\nJosephson farm, two miles east of\nWashburn, at 9 a. m., and the Louis\nConklin farm, five miles west and\ntwo miles north of Garrison, at 1:30\np. m.\nAmong the novel features included\nin New York\u2019s 63-story Doherty\nbuilding will be double-decked eleva\ntors which will take on and dis\ncharge passengers at two floors sim\nultaneously.\nA i ft- _\nw oF itV* i\nir s QRY i\nTHE TEXAS COMPANY, Texaco Petroleum Product* ML \u2019%ATM E\nTEXACO A ETHYL tAAVeU ETHYL 1\nVwSSSS&teN.\u2122 THE DRY ANTI-KWOCK GASOLINE\nSnnwmitwww \u201d3\nH ipiTii,EW.;j,nu. in ,M '.'HLW IT J.JAJUJ 1 I .Si\nBy Williams\ncorporation\nFEEDER STOCK MUST\nSHOW HEALTH PROOF\nShipmsnts Into North Dakota\nShould First Bo Taken Up\nWith Livestock Board\nFeeder cattle coming into North\nDakota must be accompanied by a\nhealth certificate, according to B. K.\nBJornson, assistant state veterinarian.\nThe health certificate must show that\nthe cattle are free from symptoms of\nany communicable disease. They\nshould be branded with the letter F\non the right Jaw and held separate\nfrom the other cattle on the farm\nand can be shipped only to market,\nunless the owner has the cattle tested\nupon arrival.\nThe State Livestock Sanitary board,\nBismarck, should be advised of any\nintended shipments and consulted\nwith reference to necessary permits\nfor inspection upon arrival. When\napplying for the permit the number\nof cattle and location of premises\nshould be given.\nSheep also require a health certif\nicate indicating that the animals are\nfree from symptoms of scabies or lip\nand leg ulceration or from exposure\nthereto within 30 days prior to ship\nment.\nHogs require a health certificate\nstating that no infectious swine dis\nease exists or has existed in the lo\ncality from which the swine origi\nnated within six months prior to date\nof shipment, unless the swine are\ncertified by a duly accredited federal\nor approved veterinarian as having\nbeen immunised by the DSrset-Mc-\nBride-Niles anti-hog cholera serum\nand virus applied not leas than 30\ndays before date of shipment.\nLegion Band Will\nVisit Seven Towns\nFargo, N. D., Oct. 3.\u2014-(fl*) \u2014ln natty\nnew uniforms, members of the North\nDakota American Legion band, which\nGeneral Pershing once described as\n\u201cthe UveUest band in the world are\ngoing to make a tour of the stfcte,\nopening in Fargo October 17 and\nclosing at Wahepton October 35 The\nband will give parades and concerts\nin seven cities\u2014Fargo, Hillsboro,\nMayville, Jamestown, Valley City,\nLisbon* and Wahpeton.\nTests Reliability\nOf Average Witness\nBoston, Oct. 3.\u2014Dr. Walter Frank\nlin Prince has just published an ar\nticle dealing with an experiment con\nducted some time ago testing the un\nreliability of witnesses. In a scene eet\nespecially for the test, witnesses were\nasked to write down their account of\nwhat happened and what was heard.\nEvery one of the twenty witnesses\u2019\naccounts differed.\nMENOKEN SCHOOL FIRST CLASS\nWITH FOUR-TEAR HIGH COURSE\nStudents Are Organized to Con\nduct Various Auxiliary\nActivities\n(Editor\u2019s Note: The following ar\nticle about the Menoken Consolidated\nschool was written by students of that\nInstitution. The Tribune prints it\nherewith as evidence of its interest\nin the advancement cf education in\nBurleigh county and its interert in\nBurleigh county\u2019s school children.\nBimilar articles on other schools will\nbe printed from time to time.)\nAbout 35 years ago there was a\nframe school houco in Mencken, sit\nuated where the c!d one now is. One\nSunday it burned, from some un\nknown cause, although some think\nit was from the boys smoking in it.\nThere was another school in section\n10. This school house still stands.\nAfter the one in Menoken burned, a\nstone building was built, which ac\ncommodated all the \u201cpupils until the\nwinter of 1039. That year the fifth,\nsixth, seventh, and eighth grades\nmoved into .tbs froht part of the pool\nhall. The lower grades stayed in the\nold school\n,In the new school, which 13 consol\nidated, there are four large class\nrooms, a library, and a principal's\nroom. Modem facilities and equip\nment are In use here. Electric lights,\nwater fountains and a hot water\nheating system are among these\nA four-year high school course Is\noffered this year, which is an Im\nprovement over preceding years. We\nhave also organised a junior high\nschdol.\nThe people of the community, as\nwell as the pupils of the .school, are\nvery happy to know that we how have\na first class consolidated school. This\nentitles us to much moye benefit fro{n\nthe state aid fund than ever before.\nDuring the last school term (1929-\n30) the Menoken consolidated school\nreceived two triple swings and a slide.\nThis year two merry-go-rounds were\nput up. We also have equipment for\noutdoor basketball. Later on, when\nIt becomes too cold to play basketball\nout of doors, we hope that the Mfe\nnoken town hall will be equipped so\nthat we can play there.\nWe have received an excellent set\nof maps of the ancient world for use\nIn Bible study and ancient history.\nFurther equipment includes 13* new\ndesks, a desk and chair for the teach\ner, a new dictionary, a new flag, and\na bulletin board.\nNow Enrolls 79\nThis year we have a total enroll\nment of 79. There are 22 pupils in\nthe primary room, 26 in the inter\nmediate room, 16 in the junior high\nroom, and 15 in the senior high room.\nA number of children from other\ntownships are attending. From\nBoyd township we have Clarence\nDoppler, Conrad Welch, Paul Snyder,\nStanley McCurdy, and Robert Gar\nvoss, all In high school, and Elmer\nthe sixth grade and Elsie\nMills in the first grade. Stanley\nKnudtson from Apple Creek and\nArthur Halvorson from Shrunk town\nship are In high school\nHighly Trained Teachers\nWe have four teachers this year,\none more than last year. sWa have\nMiss Blanche Stewart, primary room,\ngrades 1,2, 3, of Valley City, a grad\nuate of the Standard course of the\nTeachers college at Valley City. Miss\nLillian* Newman, room,\ngrades 4,5, 6, of Golden Valley a\ngraduate of the Dickinson Normal.\nMrs. Ruth Reltsel, Junior High school\nteacher, Is a graduate of the stand\nard course of the Teachers college at\nMayville. Miss Sara Boyd, a grad\nuate of the Jamestown college, is\nprincipal and teacher-of the senior\nhigh school.\nNew Students Association\nA week ago .Friday the junior and\nsenior high school rooms met to or\nganize a Students* association.\nOhe purpose of this association is\nto take charge of all business wnich\npertains to our school activities, such\nas our new baseball team, basketball,\nand kitten ball It will also sponsor\nour parties and weekly programs.\nAlthea King was elected precedent,\nStanley McCurdy, vice president, and\nRoberta Craven, secretary. .Althea\nhas nominated a committee of three\nto draw up the constitution for our\nassociation.\nBhe is going to appoint a program\ncommittee whose duty is to prepare a\nprogram for each Friday afternoon.\nThese programs are going to be edu\ncational. They will give every mem\nber a chance to practice self-expres\nsion.\nDuring our second meeting, Mabel\nWood was elected editor of our pa\nper and sohool colors were chosen,\nblue and silver.\nHoM Fall Picnic\nLast Friday, September 26. the\nMenoken school held a picnic at the\npicnic grounds about one and a half\nmiles from the school.\nAs soon as we got there we busied\nourselves getting plenty of wood for\nthe bonfires. Tfcpn every one receiv\ned a stick so that they could roast\nwieners. For lunch we had sand\nwiches, wieners, potato salad, cook\nies, and fruit nectar.\nAfter lunch we played several\ngames and ate some nice Juicy apples.\nWhile we were playing Ramus\nRoberson had the misfortune of cut\nting one of his fingers quite badly.\nThe buses took the smaller chil\ndren. The older ones were supposed\nto walk, but In the end there were\nOnly a.few who really walked clear\nto the picnic grounds.\nAll had, a very nice time although\nit was rather chilly out that day.\nNAMED ON COMMITTEE\nMiles City, Mont., Oct 3.\u2014(/P) Rev.\nH. 8. Brewster, Fargo, was named a\nmember of the executive committee\nof the synod of the northwest of the\nEpiscopal church. Casper, Wyo., was\nchosen as the 1932 convention city.\nROOSEVELT CABIN\nVISITED BY 8,125\nNino Outside Countries Repre\nsented by 60 Tourists;\n3,508 From Statss\nRegistration of visitors at Roosevelt\ncabin, on the capitol grounds, totaled\n8.125 from .Tune 1 when the memor\nial was opened, to September 27, when\nit was closed for the season, Mrs. Lou\nOsborn, registrar, reports.\nNew Mexico and Rhode Island #ere\nthe only states not represented lo the s\nvisitors. Mrs. Osborn reports.\nMany of the visitors came to study\nthe native flora in the garden sur\nrounding the cabin.\nNot all of the visitors were frbm\nthe states, however. Sixty came from\nforeign lands. The majority of these\nwere from Canada, from which 44\ntourists registered. Others from\nabroad classified: Hawaii, five; Phil\nippines, five; and one each from Ger\nmany, China, England, Scotland, Den-\nmark and Russia. North and South\nDakota registrations led the states,\nwith 4,617 and 710. respectively, in a r\nstates registration of 2,508. The num- zi\nbets from the other states were:\nMinnesota, 683; Nebraska, 439;\nlowa. 300: Wisconsin, 245; Montana,\n193; Illinois 174; California, 92; Mich-\nigan, 64; Washington, 62; Missouri,\n59; Indiana. 51; Ohio. 42; Kansas. 34;\nPennsylvania. 33; New York, 33;\nTexas, 30; Oklahoma, 18; Florida,\n20; New Jersey. Wyoming and Wash- J\nington, D. C., each, 15; Colorado, 14;\nTennessee, 13; Oregon, 12; Idaho. 10;\nVirginia, 9; North Carolina, 8; Ken-\ntucky, 7; Vermont, Massachusetts and\nMaryland, each 4; Maine and Con-\nnectlcut, each, 3; South Caro- r\nlira, Alabama and Nevada, each 2;\nNew Hampshire, Delaware. Georgia,\nMississippi, Arkansas, Louisiana,\nArizona. Utah and Alaska, each 1.\nAn elevator to raise and lower a\nmovie camera is now in use.\nSummer\nCOLDS\nAlmost everybody knows hOw\nBayer Aspirin breaks up a cold\u2014\nbut why not prevent it? Take a\ntablet or two when you first feel\nthe cold coming on. Spare vourself\nthe discomfort of a summer cold.\nRead the proven directions in every\npackage for headaches, pain, etc.\nnr","height":"29286","width":"22584"}}
